{"Q0":"I felt that I judged whether an agent seemed more human or more fake based on whether it followed the pattern of where I directed my attention, but also based on how much attention the agent would pay to faces, signs/writing, and whether their attention would come back to the same spot (like a \"double-take\") to try and figure out what something was."}

{"Q0":"I found the experiment easiest when there were a lot of faces involved because I knew that an average human being would spend most of their time assessing faces than they would the surrounding environment. If the attention didn't immediately go to faces, I would automatically kind of assume that it was fake. Additionally, I found that I would sometimes glance multiple times at something that was oddly shaped or confusing or stand-out, and if the attention did a similar thing, it also seemed more human to me. Also, if the person seemed to be paying attention to signage, writing, or bold colors, that pointed to it being human."}
{"Q0":"I found landscapes most difficult because often they did not have any extremely stand out features and your eye can naturally kind of drift anywhere. "}
